segments.text: In 1976 at 12 noon, I, Nancy Huber, interviewed Mrs. Freda Box.
She has been a resident of Bryan, Texas proper since 1952, and she lived near Bryan for the most part of her life.
Mrs.
Box is now working at the Texas Agricultural Extension Service on the Texas A&M campus in College Station, Texas.
First of all,
How long ago did your family come to the area to bond?
When I was eight years old.
My parents moved to, not in town, but out in the country.
In the country.
Uh-huh.
And where were you born?
Duval, Texas.
Duval?
Uh-huh.
Duval, Texas.
What year?
Um, why did your family decide to move to this area?
Do you have a lot of relatives around here?
No.
My immediate family is in this country.
That was my maiden name.
Schultz?
Uh-huh.
German.
Yes.
Are there a lot of German people around?
I mean, of the white people that are in this area, are they German?
Well, around the Curtin area, the majority are German.
Okay.
Were you born in your home or not in a hospital?
Did the doctor come to your house?
He did.
Okay.
Do you have any brothers or sisters?
Yes, I have two sisters and two brothers.
And I guess you started school here.
Well, I'm in the little edge community.
It's about 20 miles out from Fulton-Grasses County.
From Grasses County.
That's neat.
And how did you get there?
I rode a little donkey with a neighbor boy.
You rode a donkey?
Yeah.
I mean, do most people just get their horse or something?
Well, horses are buddies.
I walked.
If they were close enough, they wouldn't have buses being out there.
Yeah.
How far were you from the school?
about four months.
Four more people.
That's interesting.
What did you, what kind of things did you do for leisure time activities?
Where did young people go to meet other young people?
Well, we had our community gatherings, you know, little parties in the house, mostly.
And then at the schoolhouse we'd have gatherings and programs.
plays and stuff like that more than they do now, I think.
Yeah, I guess the school was more of a...
It was a means of getting the people together again.
Yeah.
Um, was there just one schoolhouse?
How was the school set up?
Was it just one building with not one classroom?
I believe we had two buildings in our school when I was... One teacher taught the whole grade, too.
They're not divided like they are now.
Each teacher had a room.
Mm-hmm.
They had that same teacher all the way through that year.
What did you do on Sundays?
Well, most of the time, if we went to Sunday school and then we'd gather with our friends, maybe walk across the way to
We'd be a bunch of us, get together, we'd go walking in the Bluzard, I don't know, highway or something, you know, maybe at one of those homes.
So it was kind of generally a kind of get together.
It was.
More than now you have to work or something.
Kind of that.
What kind of things did you do on holidays, such as Easter, Thanksgiving, was there any, Fourth of July, was there any kind of community thing?
Well, usually there'd be a picnic on Fourth of July.
just about everybody in the community would go.
It would be down on the river bank or at the community center or somewhere like that.
Did they have fireworks?
Some, but not as much as they do now or in later years.
Do you recall any fads, anything, fashions that was the thing to do?
Any dances?
What kind of dances did you do?
I didn't dance.
I never danced.
You never danced?
I mean, the kids around.
Yeah, they did.
They did the Charleston and the waltz and stuff like that.
Was there a lot of country-western?
I don't know.
Folk and waltz music mostly, I imagine.
Yeah.
I don't know too much about that.
I don't know too much about country-western, so.
Okay.
Could you tell me about your first job and what kind of pay you had?
Well, when I was growing up, you know, the working public jobs, all we did then was maybe help somebody in the fields or somewhere.
The week before I married, I worked one whole week to make enough money to buy my wedding dress.
We got 50 cents a day and worked from sunup to sundown.
What kind of work did you do?
I worked in corn.
I was out in the cornfield all by myself that whole week.
Wow.
When did you get married?
And where did you and your husband live?
We lived out there for a while, and later we had moved to Houston when the war came on.
Ah, you moved to Houston.
Okay.
We lived there three years.
People were going to shoot me in those years.
Was that your reason for moving to Houston?
For the job or what?
Well, I don't know.
It was just a good opportunity for us.
Pretty good pay.
More than we've been, like, you know, a farm or something.
Yeah.
Your family then, your father, I guess, you were farmers?
Uh-huh.
And what kind of things, you know, corn, I guess, what else?
Corn, cotton, and vegetables, of course.
Maybe some hay and peanuts.
Mm-hmm.
You didn't just, you know, you sold a lot of this stuff.
You didn't just, it wasn't just for your family, right?
We sold what come and a lot of corn too.
But then the vegetables and stuff like that.
The hay was for our own use.
For your own use.
If you can.
But we just wanted a small scale of what the family could do.
Yeah.
You know, you don't have big farms generally like you do now.
How many acres ?
We might have farmed about 60 or 70, something like that.
What changes have you noticed?
OK, so you went to Houston.
You were there for three years.
That was during the war.
Everybody was called in to register them.
But he had family.
He was a little older than the general draft age, too, so it would get what it gets for him.
During the Depression, what kind of things do you remember?
Would it be as hard to get, you know, food, appliances?
Some of it said, you know, it was really difficult to get appliances.
Did you have any troubles like that?
I don't guess we had very many of them back then, honey, except the icebox.
Yeah.
We didn't have electricity or anything then.
We just laid out in the forehead.
Yeah.
So I don't really know.
Of course, we raised a lot of our food, so we really never did suffer from food like a lot of people did.
Yeah.
So you were, generally speaking, as far as just surviving, you were a lot better off than a lot of people?
Yes, we were.
We were black for food or, you know, the comforts of home.
Yeah, right.
Okay, did people used to travel a lot to other towns?
Well, first of all, when did you move back to the San Diego?
After the war, in about 44.
About 44.
Well, I didn't go to the course to eventually get paid.
When I was just a job, well, they'd travel in a wagon or a buggy when they wanted to go somewhere.
Of course, that would maybe like to know how to chill, come to town once in a while.
But about the extent of your travels,
We could go visit relatives or something in another town.
Yeah, yeah.
And what were, what different towns did, you know, people go to?
I mean, what other towns were, you know, kind of a big place to go?
We went to Houston sometimes because we had relatives there.
We went to Elkhart and Palestine.
That's where my husband's family lived.
So, mostly he went where he went visiting, you know, rather than sightseeing it.
Just on vacations like you do now.
Have you ever been out of Texas?
Oh, yes.
I went on several vacation trips.
We went on through the north and the northwest.
I've never been east.
I've been to Kansas City.
You just went on vacation?
Yes.
Do you have any children?
Yes, we have six children.
They are all grown and married.
Were they raised in this area?
Yes.
They are all brought in schools.
Okay, you came back to this area after you moved to Houston, after the loan.
Did you, were you then moved, did you move into Brown?
No, not directly.
We still moved back to Edge Farm three years.
Then we moved into the Tabor community.
We lived out there about three years.
And in 1951, we moved into Brown.
I see.
Why did you go into the Tabor community?
Well, it was just, we bought a little farm out there.
We sued for truck farming.
That's what we wanted to do.
They started being like with their paper wraps and stuff like that.
It was more convenient to move to town.
I started working in town.
I had heard that New Tabor at one time was a really prosperous place.
I don't know if that was when you were there or any more.
It was Tabor, no.
Not New Tabor?
No.
Ah, okay.
Exactly, like five, six miles to the north.
And what area of Brownie did you stay on when you turned 51?
On Sandy Point Road, we waged 25th, and I still live in that same house.
Really?
I lost my husband four years ago.
One of my boys lives with me, but he's not married at the time.
Yeah.
So have your children mainly stayed in the area or moved on?
Well, one lives in Colorado and one family lives in Dallas.
One of the boys lives in Camp Creek.
He's postman from my area.
He comes in to work every day.
One daughter and one son live here in town.
So they generally stayed in the area.
Close, yes.
Yeah.
Okay.
Um, going back to the, well, I was thinking, I had already talked about the world, okay, but
Do you remember things that people did for the war to contribute to, you know, the effort?
Whether, I don't know, you know, just a real simple example is like we, I think my parents, you know, they separate their trash and stuff with cans and bottles and everything like that.
It could be, you know, or they just, you know, or women going and working in factories or whatever.
Well, I did, I did, because I had as much of a loss for all of that at that time.
We bought war bonds.
What was the advantage of war bonds?
Well, if you kept them so long, you got, you know, you made an interest on them, it was like you were doing a savings account.
You could still buy savings bonds, you know.
They'd take it out of your salary, and then you'd
I always hear these things, but I guess unless you're even part of it, you don't know that.
Okay, do you recall anything from like presidential elections, campaigns, who the people voted, or anything?
Not really.
I remember real well when Pastor Roosevelt
Was he pretty popular with the people through this whole administration?
He was kind of like President Kennedy.
Everybody liked him.
He died when it was a shock to me.
Yeah, it was really shocking.
We're starting to lose it.
Were there any great disasters, like floods?
Not necessarily great disasters, but things that really affected the community.
Floods, tornadoes, droughts?
Well, there were droughts, yes.
Sometimes we formed in the river bottom in the same volume where we had
big rains that would flood our farmland, maybe destroy our crops.
Usually it would be early in the spring or maybe in the fall after the cotton and stuff was made and they were just about ready.
Several times I remember they would get that water covered the whole field.
And since you just farmed, so you really didn't have things to go back on.
back then.
They used to do the merchants would help the farmers, you know, they could borrow money to live on the farm with them.
Then when they made money, they would pay it back.
Sometimes you'd go in debt for a year.
If you had a good year, you'd pay up.
Do you remember
I guess when we lived in the city of Vine, things, racial things, or even outside, like this area was primarily blacks, and were there a lot, I don't know about Vine, really.
Well, yeah, they were divided, but I mean, most blacks lived over on the west and northwest side, which they still do to a big extent.
But there wasn't any trouble when they started upgrading the schools, like there was a lot of places.
I want to say some of the kids might have gotten scuffles or something like that, but there wasn't anything to do over it, you know, between the citizens and all.
What prompted them to go ahead and integrate?
Was it a cold order?
It was an impulsory thing.
It was an impulsory thing.
What was that?
Six or eight years ago, I don't know what everybody came to.
What about Mexicans?
Are there a lot in this area?
Yes, quite a few.
Well, I guess over on the west side and south side there's more, but they're kind of mingling with the other people more or less now.
They know more than they used to be.
They used to come in here from Mexico to do farm work instead.
They can't do that anymore.
So those that live here just work somewhere I would be.
There's not too much people working in the highway department.
operating equipment or even jobs on the campus and stuff like that, just like everybody else.
Yeah.
I was going to ask you, what big changes have you seen in the technology of farming?
I mean, there are a lot, but what have you noticed?
Well, there's not very many small farms like we've had anymore.
I mean, it's got soil, you know, expensive to farm.
They may have to farm on a big scale.
And the farming has gone to the big farmers where it used to be these little plots here and there.
The people that most of them that lived on these little farms have moved to town because they couldn't make a living on these little farms.
Was farming, you say, on a small farm?
It was mainly a family thing, and then whatever extra they had there.
What impact do you think this university has had on the growth and development of the area?
It's responsible for just the biggest part of the growth, because it brings so many people in here and gets work to so many others, too.
I feel like it's just about a half of us.
Has put you on the map, maybe.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Did you notice, you know, when the university turned to co-ed, was there any reaction to that, good or bad?
Oh, some thought they didn't like for the girls to come here, but it didn't make any difference.
Yeah.
What type of changes have you noticed in the landscape, like roads, ground roads, and transportation?
Of course, the roads have built up a lot, and we've got lots of new streets in our town since it has grown so much.
Not all roads were fixed.
Like 29th Street, it was just a very old road, even until about 15 years ago.
I imagine they just fixed it a little later.
That's a part of town.
Yeah, that's pretty much a man.
Any railways that you have?
Well, I don't expect the railroads are even as busy as they were in those days, because they didn't want to work by rail.
And they stopped the passenger trains.
The freight trains come through now.
The same tracks we always had.
Did people travel a lot on the passenger trains?
They used to.
What big differences do you see, like when you were raised and things you used to do, and when you raised your children?
We always lived out where our children had room to roam around.
I think it has a lot to do with the way children are now.
They're so cooped up.
They don't feel free to go to places like our children did then.
Nobody cared for hunting or fishing or just roaming over the place.
And now, if you get off of the highways or your own place, well, you're trespassing it.
So they had more freedom to work off their energy, I think, that may be one reason for the restlessness in children now, I feel like it is.
And what kind of, what like with the radio?
Did you use to, did you have radio when you were young?
No, when I was a child and ever since I've been there, I've just come out with my radio.
And you used to listen to the... We used to listen to music.
We used to listen to stories on radio before we got a TV.
Yeah?
What, what, do you recall any that were popular on radio?
The O.H.B.
Yeah.
Really?
like gangbusters and things like that.
You know, you take these stories, these stories take a lot of things.
Yeah.
What about television when it came into the area?
I mean, what did people think of, you know, television personally?
Well, at first it was kind of scattered, few and far between.
They were just people that were more, I guess, wealthier people or...
you know, what are the good circumstances could afford them for the virus to have been a weird species when they first came out.
Do you remember when just the idea of it was that people said, and I think that was really strange, like to me I think talking on the telephone and seeing somebody is really weird.
I don't know.
Do you have

friends or relatives that have moved away from the area for any particular reason, maybe economic or, you know, because there wasn't enough here or they have moved into the area because they just want to go somewhere else?
All of my family was German.
My brothers and sisters.
They all married German boys, but me, I married an American boy.
I really messed things up for them.
Was your husband from Germany?
No, my husband wasn't German.
Excuse me, I'm saying the others.
My grandparents came from Germany.
But of course my mother dated people.
They were from South Texas.
Which area in South Texas?
Over in Victoria and Yoakum and down in that area.
You know, my relatives on my mother's side were German.
They're in Edmond and Yocum and all that area.
You know, Edmond is right near Victoria.
I still have relatives in Yocum.
The rice is in Yocum.
I know why, but I have relatives in Yocum.
That's interesting.
So I miss a lot of Germany.
This area has a lot of Germans.
I believe it's, most of the people down there, I believe it's kind of a German settlement.
Okay, well, I think that's all I have to say right now, Ms. Fox.
I'd like to thank you very much for coming and taking this time out of your lunchtime to talk with me and get this interview.
I appreciate it.
Thank you.
